title: Please read and be informed!
description:
When you undermine my instructions, you're undermining the farmer.¬† I get my instructions from them. 

Leviticus 19:9-10 "When you reap the harvest of your land, do not reap to the very edges of your field or gather the gleanings of your harvest. 10. Do not go over your vineyard a second time or pick up the grapes that have fallen. Leave them for the poor and the foreigner. I am the Lord your God."

The produce we glean is for our neighbors in need. We don't pay for it and we ask that no one sells it.¬† Some farms have produce stands and if you can afford it, support our farmers by buying at their stand. (I normally include info on email.)

SoSA relies on the farmer to call me, I don't call them.¬† They plan, but it doesn't mean it will be ready. Hint: weather and many other reasons.

We get a short notice, 3-4 days and sometimes 1 day. An e-mail goes out immediately, or as soon as I can. I may also call depending on number of people needed.

Please DON'T show up to a farm unannounced and definitely don't wander around the farm.¬† It is rude and disrespectful to the farmers.¬†¬†

Spots are limited and they're first come first serve basis.¬† PLEASE NOT NOT ask me to add you automatically, if I do it for one, I'd have to do it for everyone. If the event is at capacity, let me know you wish to be put on a waiting list, if someone cancels I will contact you.

ONE EMAIL per person.¬† Please don't sign up two people using the same email address. Remember, spots are limited and when unregistered volunteers show up, it causes delays and may cause problems with the farm.¬† I rely on the farm to tell me how many spots to open.¬†

We accept volunteers of all ages, children under 16 must be with an adult and no need to sign them up online.¬† Let me know ahead of time and I will have a paper waiver to fill out.¬† This will allow an adult to have that spot. If your teen needs volunteer hours, I will sign them.¬† If they drive themselves, their driving time is included.¬†

We glean for 2 hours only and that includes leaving for the field, so I ask that you arrive at least 15 minutes early. IF you are late, you will be left behind.¬† This is to respect the farmers and everyone else who showed up on time.

Gleanings are from 8-10am, with the exception of a farm in Concord. We glean from 7:30-9:30.

Sometimes we may have the chance to return to the field as second time, however most of the time the farm is waiting for us to finish so they bushhog the field and get it ready for the next crop. See picture!

Most of our farms do not have a bathroom for us to use and the woods do not count as one.¬† Please plan accordingly!

A handwashing station is provided, (soap/water) you are welcome to bring your own clean gloves.¬† If using gloves, we ask that you keep up with them so we don't litter the field.¬† It can get stuck in farm machinery and cause expensive damage.

If you are taking produce back to an agency, information must be provided prior to gleaning, (address, EIN, contact info, etc.)¬† Also, anyone delivering produce must bring their own boxes to transport the gleanings.

If you have a clean bucket, please bring it, they are easier to carry in a field than boxes.

It gets HOT in the field, if you need a break take it.¬† Wear a hat and bring plenty of water to drink.

No pets are allowed and service dogs are left to the farmer's discretion,¬† it must be cleared prior to the date of gleaning.¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†

Dress for the occasion.¬† Closed toe shoes required! Fields can be muddy and tennis shoes are not practical.¬†

Sometimes we may all drive our vehicles to the field, sometimes just trucks and other times no vehicles are allowed and we will all ride on a wagon, oh... and sometimes we walk. Please follow instructions and if you have questions, ask.¬† Don‚Äôt assume that you can drive your vehicle just because ‚Äúthere is space‚Äù.

We glean when the agencies are open, Monday-Friday. 

If you have a large group call me about spaces.  If we schedule months in advance, the chances of something coming up are slim to none.  Again, we work work with the farmer, not the other way around. 

If you read all this.... THANK YOU and give yourself a high five. :)
